         <entryFree xml:id="chiwei" type="architectural-feature">
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin" type="preferred" source="#biblk000009-1">chīwěi</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#biblk000009-2">鴟尾</term>
         	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">鴟尾</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-4" xml:lang="Wade-Giles" source="#biblk000009-3">ch'ih-wei</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-5" xml:lang="en" type="literal_translation">owl tail; hawk tail</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-6" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000009-4">sea beast</term>
            <note type= "Scope Note (brief)">
                  <p xml:lang="en">In traditional Chinese architecture, refers to dramatic, curved tiles located at both ends of the roof main ridge. The term appears in official statutory documents regulating the types and grades of buildings that can use chiwei, thus it would have been a marker of high status. There are provisions for the sizes, practices, power limits, and regulations for the Chiwei used on buildings in the Yingzao Fashi (1103, 13.5a-b).</p>
                  <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">鴟尾指建築正脊兩端的瓦作構件。《陳書》、《宋史》等官修史書中對於可以使用鴟尾的建築類型和等級具有規定，從文獻記載中可推論鴟尾壹般用於高等級建築。1103年出版的《營造法式》中對用於不同規格的建築上的鴟尾的尺寸、做法、功限、料例有所規定。</p>
